07387nam a22007215i 9780822396406DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19941994ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223964067 a10.1515/97808223964062doi  a(DE-B1597)553002  a(OCoLC)1226678501  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a34022000aConstitutionalism, Identity, Difference, and Legitimacy :bTheoretical Perspectives /cMichel Rosenfeld. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1994] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (448 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tI Introduction -- tModem Constitutionalism as Interplay Between Identity and Diversity -- tII The Rebirth of Constitutionalism -- tA New Birth of Constitutionalism: Genetic Influences and Genetic Defects -- tIII Constitutionalism as Bridge Between Self and Other: The Politics and Legitimation of Constitution Making -- tConstitutional Bootstrapping in Philadelphia and Paris -- tRevolution and Constitutionalism in America -- tConstitutional Powermaking of the New Polity: Some Deliberations on the Relations Between Constituent Power and the Constitution -- tDilemmas Arising from the Power to Create Constitutions in Eastern Europe -- tIV The Identity of the Constitutional Subject and the Search for Authoritative Constitutional Meaning -- tGerman Constitutional Culture in Transition -- tConstitutional Identity -- tReactionary Constitutional Identity -- tToward a First Amendment Jurisprudence of Respect: A Comment on George Fletcher's Constitutional Identity -- tHermeneutics and Constitutional Interpretation -- tThe Constitutional Judge: Master or Slave of the Constitution? -- tA Philosophical Reconstruction of Judicial Review -- tv Freedom, Equality, Individuals, Groups, and the Struggle Between Identity and Difference -- tPreferred Generations: A Paradox of Restoration Constitutions -- tFree Speech and the Cultural Contingency of Constitutional Categories -- tThe Multicultural Self: Questions of Subjectivity, Questions of Power -- tVI On Drawing Constitutional Boundaries Between Self and Other: The Role of Property Rights -- tOn Property and Constitutionalism -- tTransitional Constitutions -- tINDEX -- tCONTRIBUTORS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInterest in constitutionalism and in the relationship among constitutions, national identity, and ethnic, religious, and cultural diversity has soared since the collapse of socialist regimes in Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union. Since World War II there has also been a proliferation of new constitutions that differ in several essential respects from the American constitution. These two developments raise many important questions concerning the nature and scope of constitutionalism. The essays in this volume-written by an international group of prominent legal scholars, philosophers, political scientists, and social theorists-investigate the theoretical implications of recent constitutional developments and bring useful new perspectives to bear on some of the longest enduring questions confronting constitutionalism and constitutional theory.Sharing a common focus on the interplay between constitutional identity and individual or group diversity, these essays offer challenging new insights on subjects ranging from universal constitutional norms and whether constitutional norms can be successfully transplanted between cultures to a consideration of whether constitutionalism affords the means to reconcile a diverse society's quest for identity with its need to properly account for its differences; from the relation between constitution-making and revolution to that between collective interests and constitutional liberty and equality.This collection's broad scope and nontechnical style will engage scholars from the fields of political theory, social theory, international studies, and law.Contributors. Andrew Arato, Aharon Barak, Jon Elster, George P. Fletcher, Louis Henkin, Arthur J. Jacobson, Carlos Santiago Nino, Ulrich K. Preuss, David A. J. Richards, Michel Rosenfeld, Dominique Rousseau, András Sajó, Frederick Schauer, Bernhard Schlink, M. M. Slaughter, Cass R. Sunstein, Ruti G. Teitel, Robin West  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aBarak, Aharon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSajo, Andras, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArato, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobson, Arthur J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchlink, Bernhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNino, Carlos Santiago, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSunstein, Cass R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichards, David A. J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRousseau, Dominique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchauer, Frederick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFletcher, George P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElster, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenkin, Louis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlaughter, M. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosenfeld, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWest, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosenfeld, Mic